# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: search-engine-optimization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:search-engine-optimization/glossary-seo] Search engines crawl the web, following links from page to page, and index the content found.
[src:search-engine-optimization/glossary-seo] When you search, the search engine displays the indexed content.
[src:search-engine-optimization/glossary-seo] If you follow those rules closely when doing SEO for a website, you give the site the best chances of showing up among the first results, increasing traffic and possibly revenue (for e-commerce and ads).
[src:search-engine-optimization/glossary-seo] Search engines give some guidelines for SEO, but big search engines keep result ranking as a trade secret.
[src:search-engine-optimization/glossary-seo] SEO combines official search engine guidelines, empirical knowledge, and theoretical knowledge from science papers or patents.
[src:search-engine-optimization/glossary-seo] When exploring the website, crawlers should only find the content you want indexed.
[src:search-engine-optimization/glossary-seo] Write content using your visitors' vocabulary.
[src:search-engine-optimization/glossary-seo] Use text as well as images so that crawlers can understand the subject.
[src:search-engine-optimization/glossary-seo] You get most traffic when other established sites link to your site.
[src:search-engine-optimization/htmllinkelement-rel] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:search-engine-optimization/htmllinkelement-rel] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:search-engine-optimization/htmllinkelement-rel] The **`rel`** property of the `HTMLLinkElement` interface reflects the `rel` attribute.
[src:search-engine-optimization/htmllinkelement-rel] It is a string containing a space-separated list of link types indicating the relationship between the resource represented by the `<link>` element and the current document.
[src:search-engine-optimization/htmllinkelement-rel] The most common use of this attribute is to specify a link to an external style sheet: the property is set to `stylesheet`, and the `href` attribute is set to the URL of an external style sheet to format the page.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The meta element has two uses: either to emulate the use of an HTTP response header field, or to embed additional metadata within the HTML document.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] With HTML up to and including HTML 4.01 and XHTML, there were four valid attributes: `content`, `http-equiv`, `name` and `scheme`.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Under HTML 5, `charset` has been added and `scheme` has been removed.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] `http-equiv` is used to emulate an HTTP header, and `name` to embed metadata.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The value of the statement, in either case, is contained in the `content` attribute, which is the only required attribute unless `charset` is given.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] `charset` is used to indicate the character set of the document, and is available in HTML5.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Such elements must be placed as tags in the `head` section of an HTML or XHTML document.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] `meta` elements can specify HTTP headers which should be sent before the actual content when the HTML page is served from the web server to the client.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] as an alternative to the response header `Content-Type:` to indicate the media type and, more commonly needed, the UTF-8 character encoding.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] In this example, the `meta` element describes the contents of a web page.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Meta elements provide information about the web page, which can be used by search engines to help categorize the page correctly.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] They have been the focus of a field of marketing research known as search engine optimization (SEO), where different methods are used to provide a user's website with a higher ranking on search engines.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Prior to the rise of content-analysis by search engines in the mid-1990s (most notably Google), search engines were reliant on metadata to correctly classify a Web page and webmasters quickly learned the commercial significance of having the right meta element.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The search engine community is now divided as to the value of meta tags.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Some claim they have no value, others that they are central, while many simply conclude there is no clear answer but, since they do no harm, they use them just in case.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Google states they do support the meta tags "description", "robots", "google", "google-site-verification", "content-type", "refresh" and "google-bot".
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Major search engine robots look at many factors when determining how to rank a page of which meta tags will only form a portion.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Furthermore, most search engines change their ranking rules frequently.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Google have stated they update their ranking rules every 48 hours.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Under such circumstances, a definitive understanding of the role of meta tags in SEO is unlikely.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The `keywords` attribute was popularized by search engines such as Infoseek and AltaVista in 1995, and its popularity quickly grew until it became one of the most commonly used `meta` elements.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] No consensus exists whether or not the `keywords` attribute has any effect on ranking at any of the major search engines today.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] It is speculated that it does if the keywords used in the `meta` can also be found in the page copy itself.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] However, both these articles suggest that Yahoo! still makes use of the keywords meta tag in some of its rankings.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Yahoo! itself claims support for the keywords meta tag in conjunction with other factors for improving search rankings.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] In October 2009 Search Engine Round Table announced that "Yahoo Drops The Meta Keywords Tag Also" but later reported that the announcement made by Yahoo!'s Senior Director of Search was incorrect.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Google said that this may help worthy content to get noticed.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The syntax of the news meta keyword has subtle difference from custom keyword meta tag; it is denoted by "news_keywords", while the custom keyword meta tag is denoted by "keywords".
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Google News no longer takes into account keywords announced by news_keywords.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] According to Moz, "Title tags are the second most important on-page factor for SEO, after content".
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] They convey to the search engines what a given page is all about.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] It used to be standard SEO practice to include the primary and the secondary keywords in the title for better ranking.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Google has gone through various iterations of showing short or longer amounts of content from within the title tags.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Regardless, the title tags still hold importance in three different ways.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The `robots` attribute, supported by several major search engines, controls whether search engine spiders are allowed to index a page, or not, and whether they should follow links from a page, or not.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The attribute can contain one or more comma-separate values.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The `noindex` value prevents a page from being indexed, and `nofollow` prevents links from being crawled.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Other values recognized by one or more search engines can influence how the engine indexes pages, and how those pages appear on the search results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] These include `noarchive`, which instructs a search engine not to store an archived copy of the page, and `nosnippet`, which asks that the search engine not include a snippet from the page along with the page's listing in search results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Meta tags are one of the best options for preventing search engines from indexing content of a website.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The search engines Google, Yahoo! and MSN used in some cases the title and abstract of the DMOZ (aka Open Directory Project) listing of a website for the title and/or description (also called snippet or abstract) in the search engine results pages (SERP).
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] To give webmasters the option to specify that the Open Directory Project content should not be used for listings of their website, Microsoft introduced in May 2006 the new "`NOODP`" value for the "`robots`" element of the meta tags.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Google followed in July 2006 and Yahoo! in October 2006.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] By 2017, Google reported stopping the use of DMOZ, following its closure, hence, NOODP directive is ignored since.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The syntax is the same for all search engines who support the tag.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Yahoo! puts content from their own Yahoo! directory next to the ODP listing.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] In 2007 they introduced a meta tag that lets web designers opt-out of this.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Adding the `NOYDIR` tag to a page will prevent Yahoo! from displaying Yahoo!
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Google does not use HTML keyword or meta tag elements for indexing.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The Director of Research at Google, Monika Henzinger, was quoted (in 2002) as saying, "Currently we don't trust metadata because we are afraid of being manipulated." Other search engines developed techniques to penalize Web sites considered to be "cheating the system".
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] For example, a Web site repeating the same meta keyword several times may have its ranking *decreased* by a search engine trying to eliminate this practice, though that is unlikely.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] It is more likely that a search engine will ignore the meta keyword element completely, and most do regardless of how many words are used in the element.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Google does, however, use meta tag elements for displaying site links.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Additionally, enterprise search startup Swiftype considers meta tags as a mechanism for signaling relevancy for their web site search engines, even introducing their own extension called Meta Tags 2.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Meta refresh elements can be used to instruct a Web browser to automatically refresh a Web page after a given time interval.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] It is also possible to specify an alternative URL and use this technique in order to redirect the user to a different location.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Auto refreshing via a META element has been deprecated for more than ten years, and recognized as problematic before that.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The W3C suggests that user agents should allow users to disable it, otherwise META refresh should not be used by web pages.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] For Internet Explorer's security settings, under the miscellaneous category, meta refresh can be turned off by the user, thereby disabling its redirect ability.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] In Mozilla Firefox it can be disabled in the configuration file under the key name "accessibility.blockautorefresh".
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Many web design tutorials also point out that client-side redirecting tends to interfere with the normal functioning of a Web browser's "back" button.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] After being redirected, clicking the back button will cause the user to go back to the redirect page, which redirects them again.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Some modern browsers seem to overcome this problem however, including Safari, Mozilla Firefox and Opera.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Auto-redirects via markup (versus server-side redirects) are not in compliance with the W3C's – Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 1.0 (guideline 7.5).
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Meta elements of the form `<meta http-equiv="foo" content="bar">` can be used as alternatives to HTTP headers.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] For example, `<meta http-equiv="expires" content="Wed, 21 June 2006 14:25:27 GMT">` would tell the browser that the page "expires" on June 21, 2006 at 14:25:27 GMT and that it may safely cache the page until then.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] The HTML 4.01 specification optionally allows this tag to be parsed by HTTP servers and set as part of the HTTP response headers, but no web servers currently implement this behavior.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Instead, the user agent emulates the behavior for some HTTP headers as if they had been sent in the response header itself.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] Some HTML elements and attributes already handle certain pieces of meta data and may be used by authors instead of META to specify those pieces: the TITLE element, the ADDRESS element, the INS and DEL elements, the title attribute, and the cite attribute.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] An alternative to `meta` elements for enhanced subject access within a website is the use of a back-of-book-style index for the website.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] See the American Society of Indexers website for an example.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] In 1994, ALIWEB, also used an index file to provide the type of information commonly found in meta keywords attributes.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] In cases where the content attribute's value is a URL, many authors decide to use a link element with a proper value for its rel attribute as well.
[src:search-engine-optimization/meta-element] For a comparison on when it is best to use HTTP-headers, meta-elements, or attributes in the case of language specification: see here.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] SEO is commonly used as part of a broader digital marketing strategy and involves optimizing technical infrastructure, content relevance, and authority signals to improve rankings for user queries.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] The objective of SEO is to attract users who are actively searching for information, products, or services, thereby improving brand visibility, user engagement, and conversions.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Webmasters and content providers began optimizing websites for search engines in the mid-1990s as the first search engines were cataloging the early Web.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Search engine users would query the URL of a page, and then receive information found on the page, if it existed in the search engine's index.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] ALIWEB and the earliest versions of search engines required website developers to manually upload website index files in order to be searchable and widely did not utilize any form of ranking algorithm for user queries.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] The emergence of automated web crawlers would later be used to proactively discover and index websites.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] This led to website developers to optimize their website’s search signals, including the use of meta tags, to achieve greater visibility in search results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] According to a 2004 article by former industry analyst and current Google employee Danny Sullivan, the phrase "search engine optimization" came into use in 1997.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Sullivan credits SEO practitioner Bruce Clay as one of the first people to popularize the term.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In some cases, early search algorithms weighted particular HTML attributes in ways that could be leveraged by web content providers to manipulate their search rankings.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] As early as 1997, search engine providers began adjusting their algorithms to prevent these actions.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Eventually, search engines would incorporate more meaningful measures of page purpose, including the more recent development of semantic search.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Some search engines frequently sponsor SEO conferences, webchats, and seminars.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Major search engines provide information and guidelines to help with website optimization.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Google has a Sitemaps program to help webmasters learn if Google is having any problems indexing their website and also provides data on Google traffic to the website.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Bing Webmaster Tools provides a way for webmasters to submit a sitemap and web feeds, allows users to determine the "crawl rate", and track the web pages index status.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In 2015, it was reported that Google was developing and promoting mobile search as a key feature within future products, resulting in brands and marketers shifting toward mobile-first experiences.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In the 2020s, the rise of generative AI tools such as ChatGPT, Claude, Perplexity, and Gemini began to alter how users find information online, with AI-generated answers increasingly displacing traditional search results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In response, digital marketers developed new optimization approaches for LLM-based search, referred to as answer engine optimization (AEO) or generative engine optimization (GEO).
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] These terms are often used interchangeably, and other related terms exist, such as AI engine optimization (AIEO).
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Digital marketers optimizing for GEO tend to focus on content structure, authority signals, and structured data, with the goal of becoming a trusted, citable source in AI-generated responses.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In 1998, two graduate students at Stanford University, Larry Page and Sergey Brin, developed "Backrub", a search engine that relied on a mathematical algorithm to rate the prominence of web pages.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] The number calculated by the algorithm, PageRank, is a function of the quantity and strength of inbound links.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] PageRank estimates the likelihood that a given page will be reached by a web user who randomly surfs the web and follows links from one page to another.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In effect, this means that some links are stronger than others, as a higher PageRank page is more likely to be reached by the random web surfer.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Google attracted a loyal following among the growing number of Internet users, who liked its simple design.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Although PageRank was more difficult to game, webmasters had already developed link-building tools and schemes to influence the Inktomi search engine, and these methods proved similarly applicable to gaming PageRank.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Many sites focus on exchanging, buying, and selling links, often on a massive scale.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Some of these schemes involved the creation of thousands of sites for the sole purpose of link spamming.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] By 2004, search engines had incorporated a wide range of undisclosed factors in their ranking algorithms to reduce the impact of link manipulation.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] The leading search engines, Google, Bing, and Yahoo, do not disclose the algorithms they use to rank pages.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Some SEO practitioners have studied different approaches to search engine optimization and have shared their personal opinions.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Patents related to search engines can provide information to better understand search engines.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In 2005, Google began personalizing search results for each user.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Depending on their history of previous searches, Google crafted results for logged in users.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In 2007, Google announced a campaign against paid links that transfer PageRank.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] On June 15, 2009, Google disclosed that they had taken measures to mitigate the effects of PageRank sculpting by use of the nofollow attribute on links.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Matt Cutts, a well-known software engineer at Google, announced that Google Bot would no longer treat any no follow links, in the same way, to prevent SEO service providers from using no follow for PageRank sculpting.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] As a result of this change, the usage of no follow led to evaporation of PageRank.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In order to avoid the above, SEO engineers developed alternative techniques that replace no followed tags with obfuscated JavaScript and thus permit PageRank sculpting.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Additionally, several solutions have been suggested that include the usage of iframes, Flash, and JavaScript.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] As a response, in 2019, Google would change its position and started using these tags as hints as a way to better understand how to appropriately analyze and use links within their systems".
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In December 2009, Google announced it would be using the web search history of all its users in order to populate search results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] On June 8, 2010 a new web indexing system called Google Caffeine was announced.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Designed to allow users to find news results, forum posts, and other content much sooner after publishing than before, Google Caffeine was a change to the way Google updated its index in order to make things show up quicker on Google than before.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] According to Carrie Grimes, the software engineer who announced Caffeine for Google, "Caffeine provides 50 percent fresher results for web searches than our last index..." Google Instant, a real-time search feature, was introduced in late 2010 to deliver more timely and relevant results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Historically, site administrators often spent months or years optimizing websites to improve their search rankings.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] With the rise of social media platforms and blogs, major search engines adjusted their algorithms to enable fresh content to rank more quickly in search results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Google has implemented numerous algorithm updates to improve search quality, including Panda (2011) for content quality, Penguin (2012) for link spam, Hummingbird (2013) for natural language processing, and BERT (2019) for query understanding.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] These updates reflect the ongoing evolution of search technology and Google's efforts to combat spam while improving user experience.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] On May 20, 2025, Google announced that AI Mode would be released to all US users.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] AI Mode uses what Google calls a "query fan-out technique" which breaks down the search query into multiple sub-topics which generates additional search queries for the user.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] The leading search engines, such as Google, Bing and Yahoo!, use crawlers to find pages for their algorithmic search results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Pages that are linked from other search engine-indexed pages do not need to be submitted because they are found automatically.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Directory and DMOZ, two major directories which closed in 2014 and 2017 respectively, both required manual submission and human editorial review.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Google offers Google Search Console, for which an XML Sitemap feed can be created and submitted for free to ensure that all pages are found, especially pages that are not discoverable by automatically following links in addition to their URL submission console.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Yahoo! formerly operated a paid submission service that guaranteed to crawl for a cost per click; however, this practice was discontinued in 2009.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Nevertheless, SEO tools such as Semrush enable analysis of both paid and organic traffic by providing insights into cost per click and keyword performance.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Search engine crawlers may look at a number of different factors when crawling a site.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Not every page is indexed by search engines.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] The distance of pages from the root directory of a site may also be a factor in whether or not pages get crawled.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Mobile devices are used for the majority of Google searches.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In November 2016, Google announced a major change to the way they are crawling websites and started to make their index mobile-first, which means the mobile version of a given website becomes the starting point for what Google includes in their index.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] To avoid undesirable content in the search indexes, webmasters can instruct spiders not to crawl certain files or directories through the standard robots.txt file in the root directory of the domain.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Additionally, a page can be explicitly excluded from a search engine's database by using a meta tag specific to robots (usually <meta name="robots" content="noindex"> ).
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] When a search engine visits a site, the robots.txt located in the root directory is the first file crawled.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] The robots.txt file is then parsed and will instruct the robot as to which pages are not to be crawled.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] As a search engine crawler may keep a cached copy of this file, it may on occasion crawl pages a webmaster does not wish to crawl.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Pages typically prevented from being crawled include login-specific pages such as shopping carts and user-specific content such as search results from internal searches.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In March 2007, Google warned webmasters that they should prevent indexing of internal search results because those pages are considered search spam.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In 2020, Google sunsetted the standard (and open-sourced their code) and now treats it as a hint rather than a directive.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] To adequately ensure that pages are not indexed, a page-level robot's meta tag should be included.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] A variety of methods can increase the prominence of a webpage within the search results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Cross linking between pages of the same website to provide more links to important pages may improve its visibility.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Page design makes users trust a site and want to stay once they find it.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] When people bounce off a site, it counts against the site and affects its credibility.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Writing content that includes frequently searched keyword phrases so as to be relevant to a wide variety of search queries will tend to increase traffic.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Updating content so as to keep search engines crawling back frequently can give additional weight to a site.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Adding relevant keywords to a web page's metadata, including the title tag and meta description, will tend to improve the relevancy of a site's search listings, thus increasing traffic.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] URL canonicalization of web pages accessible via multiple URLs, using the canonical link element or via 301 redirects can help make sure links to different versions of the URL all count towards the page's link popularity score.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] These are known as incoming links, which point to the URL and can count towards the page link's popularity score, impacting the credibility of a website.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] SEO techniques are often classified into two broad categories: techniques that search engine companies recommend ("white hat"), and those techniques of which search engines do not approve ("black hat").
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Search engines attempt to minimize the effect of the latter, among them spamdexing.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Industry commentators have classified these methods and the practitioners who employ them as either white hat SEO or black hat SEO.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] A white hat SEO technique conforms to the search engines' guidelines.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] It's been compared to web development that promotes accessibility, although the two are not identical.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Black hat SEO attempts to improve rankings in ways that are disapproved of by the search engines or involve deception.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] A dated black hat technique involves using hidden text, either as text colored similar to the background, in an invisible div, or positioned off-screen.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Search engines like Google have strong policies against many of these tactics.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] White hat tactics tend to produce results that last a long time, whereas black hat tactics create the risk that sites may eventually be punished once the search engines discover what they are doing.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Another category sometimes used is grey hat SEO.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] This is in between the black hat and white hat approaches, where the methods employed avoid the site being penalized but do not act in producing the best content for users.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Search engines may penalize sites they discover using black or grey hat methods, either by reducing their rankings or eliminating their listings from their databases altogether.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Such penalties can be applied either automatically by the search engines' algorithms or by a manual site review.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] One example was the February 2006 Google removal of both BMW Germany and Ricoh Germany for the use of deceptive practices.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Both companies subsequently apologized, fixed the offending pages, and were restored to Google's search engine results page.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Companies that employ black hat techniques or other spammy tactics can get their client websites banned from the search results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In 2005, the *Wall Street Journal* reported on a company, Traffic Power, which allegedly used high-risk techniques and failed to disclose those risks to its clients.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] *Wired* magazine reported that the same company sued blogger and SEO Aaron Wall for writing about the ban.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Google's Matt Cutts later confirmed that Google had banned Traffic Power and some of its clients.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] SEO is one approach within digital marketing, alongside other strategies such as pay-per-click advertising and social media marketing.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Search engine marketing (SEM) is the practice of designing, running, and optimizing search engine ad campaigns.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Its difference from SEO is most simply depicted as the difference between paid and unpaid priority ranking in search results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] SEM focuses on prominence more so than relevance; website developers should regard SEM with the utmost importance with consideration to visibility as most navigate to the primary listings of their search.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] A successful Internet marketing campaign may also depend upon building high-quality web pages to engage and persuade internet users, setting up analytics programs to enable site owners to measure results, and improving a site's conversion rate.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In November 2015, Google released a full 160-page version of its Search Quality Rating Guidelines to the public, which revealed a shift in their focus towards "usefulness" and mobile local search.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In recent years the mobile market has exploded, overtaking the use of desktops, as shown in by StatCounter in October 2016, where they analyzed 2.5 million websites and found that 51.3% of the pages were loaded by a mobile device.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] The closer the keywords are together their ranking will improve based on key terms.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] SEO may generate an adequate return on investment.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] However, search engines are not paid for organic search traffic, their algorithms change, and there are no guarantees of continued referrals.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Due to this lack of guarantee and uncertainty, a business that relies heavily on search engine traffic can suffer major losses if the search engines stop sending visitors.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Search engines can change their algorithms, impacting a website's search engine ranking, possibly resulting in a serious loss of traffic.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] According to Google's CEO, Eric Schmidt, in 2010, Google made over 500 algorithm changes – almost 1.5 per day.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Industry analysts note that websites may face risks from algorithm changes that can significantly impact organic traffic.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In addition to accessibility in terms of web crawlers (addressed above), user web accessibility has become increasingly important for SEO.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Optimization techniques are highly tuned to the dominant search engines in the target market.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] The search engines' market shares vary from market to market, as does competition.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Google has maintained dominant market share in most regions, with varying percentages by market.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In markets outside the United States, Google's share is often larger, and data showed Google was the dominant search engine worldwide as of 2007.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] As of 2006, Google had an 85–90% market share in Germany.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] As of March 2024, Google still had a significant market share of 89.85% in Germany.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] As of March 2024, Google's market share in the UK was 93.61%.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] Successful search engine optimization (SEO) for international markets requires more than just translating web pages.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] It may also involve registering a domain name with a country-code top-level domain (ccTLD) or a relevant top-level domain (TLD) for the target market, choosing web hosting with a local IP address or server, and using a Content Delivery Network (CDN) to improve website speed and performance globally.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] It is also important to understand the local culture so that the content feels relevant to the audience.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] This includes conducting keyword research for each market, using hreflang tags to target the right languages, and building local backlinks.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] However, the core SEO principles—such as creating high-quality content, improving user experience, and building links—remain the same, regardless of language or region.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] By the early 2000s, businesses recognized that the web and search engines could help them reach global audiences.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] As a result, the need for multilingual SEO emerged.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In the early years of international SEO development, simple translation was seen as sufficient.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] However, over time, it became clear that localization and transcreation—adapting content to local language, culture, and emotional resonance—were more effective than basic translation.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] On October 17, 2002, SearchKing filed suit in the United States District Court, Western District of Oklahoma, against the search engine Google.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] SearchKing's claim was that Google's tactics to prevent spamdexing constituted a tortious interference with contractual relations.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] In March 2006, KinderStart filed a lawsuit against Google over search engine rankings.
[src:search-engine-optimization/search-engine-optimization] KinderStart's website was removed from Google's index prior to the lawsuit, and the amount of traffic to the site dropped by 70%.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] A **canonical link element** is an HTML element that helps webmasters prevent duplicate content issues in search engine optimization by specifying the "canonical" or "preferred" version of a web page.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] It is described in RFC 6596, which went live in April 2012.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] A major problem for search engines is to determine the original source for documents that are available on multiple URLs.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] Duplicate content issues occur when the same content is accessible from multiple URLs.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] For example, http://www.example.com/page.html would be considered by search engines to be an entirely different page from http://www.example.com/page.html?parameter=1, even though both URLs may reference the same content.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] In February 2009, Google, Yahoo and Microsoft announced support for the `canonical` link element, which can be inserted into the `<head>` section of a web page, to allow webmasters to prevent these issues.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] The canonical link element helps webmasters make clear to the search engines which page should be credited as the original.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] The canonical link element allows search engines to consolidate indexing and ranking signals from duplicate or similar pages into a single preferred URL.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] Search engines try to utilize canonical link definitions as an output filter for their search results.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] If multiple URLs contain the same content in the result set, the canonical link URL definitions will likely be incorporated to determine the original source of the content.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] "For example, when Google finds identical content instances, it decides to show one of them.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] According to Google, the `canonical` link element is not considered to be a directive, but rather a hint that the ranking algorithm will "honor strongly".
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] While the canonical link element has its benefits, Matt Cutts, then the head of Google's webspam team, has said that the search engine prefers the use of 301 redirects.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] Cutts said the preference for redirects is because Google's spiders can choose to ignore a canonical link element if they deem it more beneficial to do so.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] The canonical link element can be either used in the semantic HTML `<head>` or sent with the HTTP header of a document.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] For non HTML documents, the HTTP header is an alternate way to set a canonical URL.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] By the HTML 5 standard, the `<link rel="canonical" href="http://example.com/">` HTML element must be within the `<head>` section of the document.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] Some sites such as Stack Overflow have on-page hyperlinks which link to a clean URL of themselves.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] When the same or very similar content is accessible from multiple URLs, search engines like Google can get confused.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] Without a canonical tag, search engines don't know which version to index and rank.
[src:search-engine-optimization/url-canonicalization] This can dilute your SEO strength and cause a negative impact on your search rankings.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] A **web crawler**, sometimes called a **spider** or **spiderbot** and often shortened to **crawler**, is an Internet bot that systematically browses the World Wide Web and that is typically operated by search engines for the purpose of Web indexing (*web spidering*).
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Web search engines and some other websites use web crawling or spidering software to update their web content or indices of other sites' web content.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Web crawlers copy pages for processing by a search engine, which indexes the downloaded pages so that users can search more efficiently.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Crawlers consume resources on visited systems and often visit sites unprompted.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Issues of schedule, load, and "politeness" come into play when large collections of pages are accessed.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Mechanisms exist for public sites not wishing to be crawled to make this known to the crawling agent.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] For example, including a `robots.txt` file can request bots to index only parts of a website, or nothing at all.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The number of web pages is extremely large, and search engines do not index all web content.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Studies of late-1990s search engines found that individual engines indexed only a fraction of the then-indexable web.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Modern search engines use crawling, indexing, and ranking systems to return relevant results quickly, although not all pages are crawled, indexed, or served.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Crawlers can validate hyperlinks and HTML code.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] They can also be used for web scraping and data-driven programming.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] A web crawler is also known as a *spider*, an *ant*, an *automatic indexer*, or (in the FOAF software context) a *Web scutter*.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] A web crawler starts with a list of URLs to visit.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Those first URLs are called the *seeds*.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] As the crawler visits these URLs, by communicating with web servers that respond to those URLs, it identifies all the hyperlinks in the retrieved web pages and adds them to the list of URLs to visit, called the *crawl frontier*.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] URLs from the frontier are recursively visited according to a set of policies.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] If the crawler is performing archiving of websites (or web archiving), it copies and saves the information as it goes.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The archives are usually stored in such a way they can be viewed, read and navigated as if they were on the live web, but are preserved as 'snapshots'.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The large volume implies the crawler can only download a limited number of the Web pages within a given time, so it needs to prioritize its downloads.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The high rate of change can imply the pages might have already been updated or even deleted.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The number of possible URLs crawled being generated by server-side software has also made it difficult for web crawlers to avoid retrieving duplicate content.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Endless combinations of HTTP GET (URL-based) parameters exist, of which only a small selection will actually return unique content.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] For example, a simple online photo gallery may offer three options to users, as specified through HTTP GET parameters in the URL.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] If there exist four ways to sort images, three choices of thumbnail size, two file formats, and an option to disable user-provided content, then the same set of content can be accessed with 48 different URLs, all of which may be linked on the site.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] This mathematical combination creates a problem for crawlers, as they must sort through endless combinations of relatively minor scripted changes in order to retrieve unique content.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Given the current size of the Web, even large search engines cover only a portion of the publicly available part.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] A 2009 study showed even large-scale search engines index no more than 40–70% of the indexable Web; a previous study by Steve Lawrence and Lee Giles showed that no search engine indexed more than 16% of the Web in 1999.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] As a crawler always downloads just a fraction of the Web pages, it is highly desirable for the downloaded fraction to contain the most relevant pages and not just a random sample of the Web.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] This requires a metric of importance for prioritizing Web pages.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The importance of a page is a function of its intrinsic quality, its popularity in terms of links or visits, and even of its URL (the latter is the case of vertical search engines restricted to a single top-level domain, or search engines restricted to a fixed Web site).
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Designing a good selection policy has an added difficulty: it must work with partial information, as the complete set of Web pages is not known during crawling.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Junghoo Cho *et al.* made the first study on policies for crawling scheduling.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Their data set was a 180,000-pages crawl from the stanford.edu domain, in which a crawling simulation was done with different strategies.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The ordering metrics tested were breadth-first, backlink count and partial PageRank calculations.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] One of the conclusions was that if the crawler wants to download pages with high Pagerank early during the crawling process, then the partial Pagerank strategy is the better, followed by breadth-first and backlink-count.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] However, these results are for just a single domain.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Cho also wrote his PhD dissertation at Stanford on web crawling.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Marc Najork and Janet Wiener performed an actual crawl on 328 million pages, using breadth-first ordering.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] They found that a breadth-first crawl captures pages with high Pagerank early in the crawl (but they did not compare this strategy against other strategies).
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Abiteboul designed a crawling strategy based on an algorithm called OPIC (On-line Page Importance Computation).
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] In OPIC, each page is given an initial sum of "cash" that is distributed equally among the pages it points to.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] It is similar to a PageRank computation, but it is faster and is only done in one step.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] An OPIC-driven crawler downloads first the pages in the crawling frontier with higher amounts of "cash".
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Experiments were carried in a 100,000-pages synthetic graph with a power-law distribution of in-links.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] However, there was no comparison with other strategies nor experiments in the real Web.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Boldi *et al.* used simulation on subsets of the Web of 40 million pages from the .it domain and 100 million pages from the WebBase crawl, testing breadth-first against depth-first, random ordering and an omniscient strategy.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The comparison was based on how well PageRank computed on a partial crawl approximates the true PageRank value.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Some visits that accumulate PageRank very quickly (most notably, breadth-first and the omniscient visit) provide very poor progressive approximations.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Baeza-Yates *et al.* used simulation on two subsets of the Web of 3 million pages from the .gr and .cl domain, testing several crawling strategies.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] They showed that both the OPIC strategy and a strategy that uses the length of the per-site queues are better than breadth-first crawling, and that it is also very effective to use a previous crawl, when it is available, to guide the current one.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Daneshpajouh *et al.* designed a community based algorithm for discovering good seeds.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Their method crawls web pages with high PageRank from different communities in less iteration in comparison with crawl starting from random seeds.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] One can extract good seed from a previously-crawled-Web graph using this new method.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Using these seeds, a new crawl can be very effective.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] A crawler may only want to seek out HTML pages and avoid all other MIME types.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] In order to request only HTML resources, a crawler may make an HTTP HEAD request to determine a Web resource's MIME type before requesting the entire resource with a GET request.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] To avoid making numerous HEAD requests, a crawler may examine the URL and only request a resource if the URL ends with certain characters such as .html, .htm, .asp, .aspx, .php, .jsp, .jspx or a slash.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] This strategy may cause numerous HTML Web resources to be unintentionally skipped.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Some crawlers may also avoid requesting any resources that have a "?" in them (are dynamically produced) in order to avoid spider traps that may cause the crawler to download an infinite number of URLs from a Web site.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] This strategy is unreliable if the site uses URL rewriting to simplify its URLs.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Website owners may instruct crawlers on what resources they are allowed and forbidden to request with the robots.txt file.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] A crawler can then use that information to chose what links to follow and which to avoid.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Crawlers usually perform some type of URL normalization in order to avoid crawling the same resource more than once.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The term *URL normalization*, also called *URL canonicalization*, refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] There are several types of normalization that may be performed including conversion of URLs to lowercase, removal of "." and ".." segments, and adding trailing slashes to the non-empty path component.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Some crawlers intend to download/upload as many resources as possible from a particular web site.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] So *path-ascending crawler* was introduced that would ascend to every path in each URL that it intends to crawl.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] For example, when given a seed URL of http://llama.org/hamster/monkey/page.html, it will attempt to crawl /hamster/monkey/, /hamster/, and /.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Cothey found that a path-ascending crawler was very effective in finding isolated resources, or resources for which no inbound link would have been found in regular crawling.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The importance of a page for a crawler can also be expressed as a function of the similarity of a page to a given query. web crawlers that attempt to download pages that are similar to each other are called **focused crawler** or **topical crawlers**.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The main problem in focused crawling is that in the context of a web crawler, we would like to be able to predict the similarity of the text of a given page to the query before actually downloading the page.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] A possible predictor is the anchor text of links; this was the approach taken by Pinkerton in the first web crawler of the early days of the Web.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Diligenti *et al.* propose using the complete content of the pages already visited to infer the similarity between the driving query and the pages that have not been visited yet.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The performance of a focused crawling depends mostly on the richness of links in the specific topic being searched, and a focused crawling usually relies on a general Web search engine for providing starting points.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] An example of the focused crawlers are academic crawlers, which crawls free-access academic related documents, such as the *citeseerxbot*, which is the crawler of CiteSeerX search engine.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Other academic search engines are Google Scholar and Microsoft Academic Search etc.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Because most academic papers are published in PDF formats, such kind of crawler is particularly interested in crawling PDF, PostScript files, Microsoft Word including their zipped formats.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Because of this, general open-source crawlers, such as Heritrix, must be customized to filter out other MIME types, or a middleware is used to extract these documents out and import them to the focused crawl database and repository.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Identifying whether these documents are academic or not is challenging and can add a significant overhead to the crawling process, so this is performed as a post crawling process using machine learning or regular expression algorithms.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] These academic documents are usually obtained from home pages of faculties and students or from publication page of research institutes.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Because academic documents make up only a small fraction of all web pages, a good seed selection is important in boosting the efficiencies of these web crawlers.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Other academic crawlers may download plain text and HTML files, that contains metadata of academic papers, such as titles, papers, and abstracts.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] This increases the overall number of papers, but a significant fraction may not provide free PDF downloads.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Another type of focused crawlers is semantic focused crawler, which makes use of domain ontologies to represent topical maps and link Web pages with relevant ontological concepts for the selection and categorization purposes.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] In addition, ontologies can be automatically updated in the crawling process.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Dong et al. introduced such an ontology-learning-based crawler using a support-vector machine to update the content of ontological concepts when crawling Web pages.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The Web has a very dynamic nature, and crawling a fraction of the Web can take weeks or months.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] By the time a web crawler has finished its crawl, many events could have happened, including creations, updates, and deletions.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] From the search engine's point of view, there is a cost associated with not detecting an event, and thus having an outdated copy of a resource.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The most-used cost functions are freshness and age.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Coffman *et al.* worked with a definition of the objective of a web crawler that is equivalent to freshness, but use a different wording: they propose that a crawler must minimize the fraction of time pages remain outdated.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] They also noted that the problem of web crawling can be modeled as a multiple-queue, single-server polling system, on which the web crawler is the server and the Web sites are the queues.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Page modifications are the arrival of the customers, and switch-over times are the interval between page accesses to a single Web site.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Under this model, mean waiting time for a customer in the polling system is equivalent to the average age for the web crawler.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The objective of the crawler is to keep the average freshness of pages in its collection as high as possible, or to keep the average age of pages as low as possible.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] These objectives are not equivalent: in the first case, the crawler is just concerned with how many pages are outdated, while in the second case, the crawler is concerned with how old the local copies of pages are.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] In both cases, the repeated crawling order of pages can be done either in a random or a fixed order.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Cho and Garcia-Molina proved the surprising result that, in terms of average freshness, the uniform policy outperforms the proportional policy in both a simulated Web and a real web crawl.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] In other words, a proportional policy allocates more resources to crawling frequently updating pages, but experiences less overall freshness time from them.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] To improve freshness, the crawler should penalize the elements that change too often.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The optimal re-visiting policy is neither the uniform policy nor the proportional policy.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The optimal method for keeping average freshness high includes ignoring the pages that change too often, and the optimal for keeping average age low is to use access frequencies that monotonically (and sub-linearly) increase with the rate of change of each page.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] In both cases, the optimal is closer to the uniform policy than to the proportional policy: as Coffman *et al.* note, "in order to minimize the expected obsolescence time, the accesses to any particular page should be kept as evenly spaced as possible".
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Explicit formulas for the re-visit policy are not attainable in general, but they are obtained numerically, as they depend on the distribution of page changes.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Cho and Garcia-Molina show that the exponential distribution is a good fit for describing page changes, while Ipeirotis *et al.* show how to use statistical tools to discover parameters that affect this distribution.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The re-visiting policies considered here regard all pages as homogeneous in terms of quality ("all pages on the Web are worth the same"), something that is not a realistic scenario, so further information about the Web page quality should be included to achieve a better crawling policy.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Crawlers can retrieve data much quicker and in greater depth than human searchers, so they can have a crippling impact on the performance of a site.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] If a single crawler is performing multiple requests per second and/or downloading large files, a server can have a hard time keeping up with requests from multiple crawlers.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] As noted by Koster, the use of web crawlers is useful for a number of tasks, but comes with a price for the general community.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] A partial solution to these problems is the robots exclusion protocol, also known as the robots.txt protocol that is a standard for administrators to indicate which parts of their Web servers should not be accessed by crawlers.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] This standard does not include a suggestion for the interval of visits to the same server, even though this interval is the most effective way of avoiding server overload.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Recently commercial search engines like Google, Ask Jeeves, MSN and Yahoo!
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Search are able to use an extra "Crawl-delay:" parameter in the robots.txt file to indicate the number of seconds to delay between requests.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The first proposed interval between successive page loads was 60 seconds.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Cho uses 10 seconds as an interval for accesses, and the WIRE crawler uses 15 seconds as the default.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The MercatorWeb crawler follows an adaptive politeness policy: if it took *t* seconds to download a document from a given server, the crawler waits for 10*t* seconds before downloading the next page.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] For those using web crawlers for research purposes, a more detailed cost-benefit analysis is needed and ethical considerations should be taken into account when deciding where to crawl and how fast to crawl.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Anecdotal evidence from access logs shows that access intervals from known crawlers vary between 20 seconds and 3–4 minutes.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] It is worth noticing that even when being very polite, and taking all the safeguards to avoid overloading Web servers, some complaints from Web server administrators are received.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Sergey Brin and Larry Page noted in 1998, "... running a crawler which connects to more than half a million servers ... generates a fair amount of e-mail and phone calls.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] A parallel crawler is a crawler that runs multiple processes in parallel.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The goal is to maximize the download rate while minimizing the overhead from parallelization and to avoid repeated downloads of the same page.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] To avoid downloading the same page more than once, the crawling system requires a policy for assigning the new URLs discovered during the crawling process, as the same URL can be found by two different crawling processes.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] A crawler must not only have a good crawling strategy, as noted in the previous sections, but it should also have a highly optimized architecture.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Web crawlers are a central part of search engines, and details on their algorithms and architecture are kept as business secrets.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] When crawler designs are published, there is often an important lack of detail that prevents others from reproducing the work.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] There are also emerging concerns about "search engine spamming", which prevent major search engines from publishing their ranking algorithms.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Web crawlers typically identify themselves to a Web server by using the User-agent field of an HTTP request.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Web site administrators typically examine their Web servers' log and use the user agent field to determine which crawlers have visited the web server and how often.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The user agent field may include a URL where the Web site administrator may find out more information about the crawler.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Examining Web server log is tedious task, and therefore some administrators use tools to identify, track and verify web crawlers.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Spambots and other malicious web crawlers are unlikely to place identifying information in the user agent field, or they may mask their identity as a browser or other well-known crawler.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Web site administrators prefer web crawlers to identify themselves so that they can contact the owner if needed.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] In some cases, crawlers may be accidentally trapped in a crawler trap or they may be overloading a Web server with requests, and the owner needs to stop the crawler.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Identification is also useful for administrators that are interested in knowing when they may expect their Web pages to be indexed by a particular search engine.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] A vast amount of web pages lie in the deep or invisible web.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] These pages are typically only accessible by submitting queries to a database, and regular crawlers are unable to find these pages if there are no links that point to them.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Google's Sitemaps protocol and mod oai are intended to allow discovery of these deep-Web resources.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Deep web crawling also multiplies the number of web links to be crawled.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Some crawlers only take some of the URLs in `<a href="URL">` form.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] In some cases, such as the Googlebot, web crawling is done on all text contained inside the hypertext content, tags, or text.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Strategic approaches may be taken to target deep Web content.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] With a technique called screen scraping, specialized software may be customized to automatically and repeatedly query a given Web form with the intention of aggregating the resulting data.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Such software can be used to span multiple Web forms across multiple Websites.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Data extracted from the results of one Web form submission can be taken and applied as input to another Web form thus establishing continuity across the Deep Web in a way not possible with traditional web crawlers.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Pages built on AJAX are among those causing problems to web crawlers.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] Google has proposed a format of AJAX calls that their bot can recognize and index.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] There are a number of "visual web scraper/crawler" products available on the web which will crawl pages and structure data into columns and rows based on the users requirements.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] One of the main difference between a classic and a visual crawler is the level of programming ability required to set up a crawler.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The latest generation of "visual scrapers" remove the majority of the programming skill needed to be able to program and start a crawl to scrape web data.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The visual scraping/crawling method relies on the user "teaching" a piece of crawler technology, which then follows patterns in semi-structured data sources.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] The dominant method for teaching a visual crawler is by highlighting data in a browser and training columns and rows.
[src:search-engine-optimization/web-crawler] While the technology is not new, for example it was the basis of Needlebase which has been bought by Google (as part of a larger acquisition of ITA Labs), there is continued growth and investment in this area by investors and end-users.
